1. d4
{ Welcome to this Opening Repertoire for Black based on the Benko Gambit ! The Benko Gambit is the usual name in the English language, named after Hungarian/American Grandmaster Pal Benko. In Europe the opening is usually called Volga Gambit. This is a full repertoire vs. 1 d4 and not only includes the Benko itself after 1 d4 Nf6 2 c4 c5 3 d5 b5, but all deviations that White may go for to avoid the Gambit. In those cases I went for continuations that are in the spirit of the Benko as much as possible. There are some cases where Black has to go for a different position type, but that's chess: we need to take into account White's plans - just playing 'your thing' does not work out well. This first chapter gives you an overview of the repertoire presented in the coming chapters. }
1... Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5
{ The only dangerous alternative is covering d4 with 3 Nf3. } 3... b5
{ The actual starting position of the Benko Gambit. Black attacks the c4-pawn and is willing to sacrifice a flank pawn for compensation. Black's compensation consists of some points. Usually he is quite well developed, but he also enjoys some structural assets. In the Benko accepted he has the better pawn strucure  (one pawn island c to h pawn vs. two islands for white a+b and d-h)  and pressure along the open files. Is is recommended to study the sample games to see more ideas related to the arising position types. }
4. cxb5 { Taking the pawn is the most critical option. } 4... a6 5. bxa6
{ The absolute main line and the one you will encounter most frequently. } 5...
g6 6. Nc3 Bg7
{ This is a key move that has brought the Benko back on the map in recent years. Black had problems in the traditional main line of Bxa6, so this new idea gained momentum. }
7. e4 O-O 8. Nf3 Qa5
{ Black has the active queenside play typical of the Benko gambit. His initiative quite often last until the endgame, pressurizing White's a and b pawn. Quite often Black will get a pawn back in the process, keeping the active prospects. -------- This is a brief overview of the repertoire, please check the detailed Repertoire suggestions for more information. I hope you enjoy the repertoire and feel inspired to try out the Benko gambit and the other lines suggested here ! Good luck ! }
