1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ The very solid London System. This is not an opening that you can expect to get a sharp position against. You rather have to keep the tension and be ready to play a long game. White's structure is just too sound to fall apart quickly. }
2... c5 { If possible, I like to attack the d-pawn in Benko fashion. } 3. e3
Qb6
{ putting immeadiate pressure on White. Of course there is nothing wrong with g6, ...e6 or ...d5 either. }
4. Nc3 d6 { Keeping the tension and blunting the f4 Bishop. } 5. Rb1 g6 6. Nf3
Bg7 7. Be2 O-O
{ Black has equalised here. White's setup with Nc3 and Rb1 is not very aggressive. Long term Black may go for play on the queenside, for instance on the c-file after a later cxd4. }
