1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ The very solid London System. This is not an opening that you can expect to get a sharp position against. You rather have to keep the tension and be ready to play a long game. White's structure is just too sound to fall apart quickly. }
2... c5 { If possible, I like to attack the d-pawn in Benko fashion. } 3. e3
Qb6
{ putting immediate pressure on White. Of course there is nothing wrong with g6, ...e6 or ...d5 either. }
4. Nc3
{ Informational line: The pawn grab is possible, but allows White to draw by repeating moves or play on in a murky position. It does not seem attractive to give White that option! }
4... Qxb2 5. Nb5 Nd5 6. Rb1
{ This is the drawing line. 6 a3!? allows White to play on in a crazy position. So the bottom line is: better not take on b2. }
6... Qxa2 7. Ra1 Qb2 { and a draw as it happened in a number of games. } *

