[White "Deviations Move 2 (Tromp, London, Veresov etc)"]
[Black "Deviations Move 2 #25"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ The very solid London System. This is not an opening that you can expect to get a sharp position against. You rather have to keep the tension and be ready to play a long game. White's structure is just too sound to fall apart quickly. }
2... c5 { If possible, I like to attack the d-pawn in Benko fashion. } 3. Nf3
{ This is not a good move that easily can lead to an early loss for White. }
3... cxd4 4. Nxd4
{ Qxd4 avoids immediate disaster, but is obviously not brilliant either due to Nc6. }
4... e5 5. Bxe5 Qa5+ 6. Nc3 Qxe5 { A 'trap' that keeps claiming victims. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Deviations Move 2 (Tromp, London, Veresov etc)"]
[Black "Deviations Move 2 #26"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. g3 c5 { Again a good choice. } 3. d5 b5
{ Why not ? The early b5 makes supporting d5 with c4 more difficult for White. }
4. Bg2 d6 5. e4 g6 6. Ne2 Bg7 7. O-O O-O
{ With good chances for Black on the queenside. White is not well positioned to go for f4 and e5. }
*

