1. d4 Nf6 2. Bf4
{ The very solid London System. This is not an opening that you can expect to get a sharp position against. You rather have to keep the tension and be ready to play a long game. White's structure is just too sound to fall apart quickly. }
2... c5 { If possible, I like to attack the d-pawn in Benko fashion. } 3. d5
{ This is the most ambitious move for White, grabbing space. } 3... b5
{ I see no reason not to play in Benko spirit. } 4. Nf3
{ The position after b5 is largely unexplored, with little practical samples. }
4... Qa5+ 5. c3 Bb7
{ And White has a hard time to keep the d5 pawn. He has to complicate the game now. }
6. e4 Nxe4 7. a4 Nf6 8. Nbd2 Bxd5 9. axb5 Qb6
{ White has sacrificed a pawn for some compensation, but we don't need to be overly afraid here. Note Black's centre pawns. }
