1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 { This is the most Benko-like approach. } 3. d5 b5
{ Of course this is the move you want to play as a Benko fan. However you need to be aware that this line is somewhat risky for Black as he is not developing that quickly and weakens the queenside early on. }
4. a4 b4 5. c4
{ This move is quite popular, surprisingly. Black has some good options now: he can just play a closed position with d6/g6 etc, which leads to similar positions to the Benko with 4 Nf3 Bb7 5 a4 Qa5+ 6 Bd2 b4. There is also the idea to open the centre quickly. }
5... e6 6. Qc2 { The best move probably, preparing e4. } 6... exd5 7. cxd5 Qe7
8. Nbd2 Nxd5 9. e4 Nc7
{ With rather unclear play. I think I rather would play the closed position mentioned on move 5, but grabbing a centre pawn is very principled. }
