[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 { This is the most Benko-like approach. } 3. d5 b5
{ Of course this is the move you want to play as a Benko fan. However you need to be aware that this line is somewhat risky for Black as he is not developing that quickly and weakens the queenside early on. }
4. Bg5 Qb6
{ A tough decision at this point for Black. The Queen sortie allows to recapture on f6 with the Queen and lends some cover to the queenside pawns. However take note that Black is falling more behind in development. }
5. a4
{ White attacks the b5 pawn immediately, forcing it forward. This gains some space for Black, but note that c4 is a weak square now that a White Knight might use in the future. However the following play is rather concrete and at times a bit unusual ! }
5... b4 6. e3 { Delaying the decision about the a-pawn. } 6... h6
{ Forcing the issue immediately. } 7. Bh4 g5 8. Bg3 Ba6
{ This not the most conventional position ever, but Black seems fine to me. The Bishop on g3 is misplaced and Black is active. }
