[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1 d4 Nf6 2 Nf3 c5"]
[Black "1 d4 Nf6 2 Nf3 c5 #16"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 { This is the most Benko-like approach. } 3. d5 b5
{ Of course this is the move you want to play as a Benko fan. However you need to be aware that this line is somewhat risky for Black as he is not developing that quickly and weakens the queenside early on. }
4. Bg5 Qb6
{ A tough decision at this point for Black. The Queen sortie allows to recapture on f6 with the Queen and lends some cover to the queenside pawns. However take note that Black is falling more behind in development. }
5. a4
{ White attacks the b5 pawn immediately, forcing it forward. This gains some space for Black, but note that c4 is a weak square now that a White Knight might use in the future. However the following play is rather concrete and at times a bit unusual ! }
5... b4 6. a5 Qd6
{ I know, that looks like a beginner move ! But in fact it has a very good idea: Black attacks d5 and White has only the choice between playing c4  (putting a pawn where a piece might belong and giving up on c2-c3 to attack b4)  or taking on f6 which corrects the Black Queen's position immediately. }
7. c4 Qc7 8. Bxf6 exf6
{ This is very comfortable for Black. He will go d6/g6 etc and play for f6-f5 is possible. Note that White has no decent pawn break which is a problem for him. There are comparable positions where White has a pawn on c2 in such a structure - this means White has a clear plan with c2-c3 to attack on the queenside. After Black has provoked c4 with Qd6 !? this is out of the picture ! }
*

