[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1 d4 Nf6 2 Nf3 c5"]
[Black "1 d4 Nf6 2 Nf3 c5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 { This is the most Benko-like approach. } 3. d5
{ Informational line: } 3... g6
{ This usually leads to a Benoni without the pawn on c4, often called the Schmid Benoni. It is named after German Grandmaster Lothar Schmid, who is best known for being the arbiter in the legendary Match of the Century between Fischer and Spassky in 1972. This form of the Benoni is not as active as I like it to be in a Benko repertoire, but is certainly a playable option. Note that if White goes 4 c4 you are committed to ...g6 based approach in the Benko which might give transpositional problems. For instance, I did not like 4 c4 b5 5 cxb5 a6 6 e3 !? for Black. This is a good choice if you look for a tricky line as White vs. Benko players who allow that transposition. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1 d4 Nf6 2 Nf3 c5"]
[Black "1 d4 Nf6 2 Nf3 c5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 { Informational line: } 2... g6 3. c4 c5
{ is possible, but White might play } 4. Nc3
{ after which we have to take on d4 at some point to transpose into an English/Maroczy position that I don't like to recommend. In addition White might go d4-d5 and transpose into a main line Benoni which does not make sense to include in this repertoire. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1 d4 Nf6 2 c4 c5 White avoids 3 d5"]
[Black "1 d4 Nf6 2 c4 c5 White avoids 3 d5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nf3
{ By far the most popular way here to avoid the Benko. Alternatives are rather harmless. }
3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6
{ This position may also arise from 1 c4 c5 or 1 Nf3 c5 2 c4. Therefore knowing the lines presented here might be a good starting point to build a repertoire vs. the English Opening. }
5. Nc3 e6
{ This is the best move here. g6 is the main alternative, but 6 e4 leads to the Maroczy Bind which is as far from the spirit of the Benko as you can imagine. Our move leads to lively piece play and more active chances for Black. }
6. e4
{ This position might also arise from a Sicilian Taimanov. It is fairly harmless for Black though. }
6... Bb4 { Important in order to put pressure on White's centre. } 7. f3 d5
{ Black opens the position. f3 has weakened the dark square a lot and this is best exploited when files are opened. }
*

