{ In fact this is not the main line. The most common move here is Ne5, but this leads to some crazy lines that are extremely deeply analyzed. Black needs to remember things up to move 30 and at the end it is even only a draw. Therefore I decided to suggest something less explored. }
8. Bg2
{ This is White's best move, already played by Kasparov in one of the first games with this line vs. Vaganian in 1989. }
8... d4 9. Na4 Qa5+ 10. Bd2 Qd8
{ A funny sequence of moves. White technically is ahead in development, but the Knights have very wierd positions. Instead of Qd8 Vaganian went for Bb4 vs. Kasparov and got into trouble later. }
11. e3 d3 12. O-O Be7 13. b3 e5
{ With rather unclear play. Black might even think of playing h7-h5 soon as the guys on a4 and b5 don't help the White King all that much. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1 d4 Nf6 2 c4 c5 White avoids 3 d5"]
[Black "1 d4 Nf6 2 c4 c5 White avoids 3 d5 #13"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nf3
{ By far the most popular way here to avoid the Benko. Alternatives are rather harmless. }
3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6
{ This position may also arise from 1 c4 c5 or 1 Nf3 c5 2 c4. Therefore knowing the lines presented here might be a good starting point to build a repertoire vs. the English Opening. }
5. Nc3 e6
{ This is the best move here. g6 is the main alternative, but 6 e4 leads to the Maroczy Bind which is as far from the spirit of the Benko as you can imagine. Our move leads to lively piece play and more active chances for Black. }
6. g3 Qb6
{ This is an important part of Black's concept. He puts pressure on White's centralized Knight, forcing a commitment. }
7. Nb3 Ne5
{ Important to remember. Black needs to disturb White here, attacking the c4 pawn. }
8. e4 Bb4 { Again putting pressure on e4. } 9. Qe2
{ Looks a bit awkward, but the only way to keep material. Black also had Qc6 as an idea to attack c4 and e4. }
9... d6 10. Bd2
{ This keeps the structure sound, but leads to sharp play nevertheless. The reason: White intends to castle queenside ! }
10... O-O { a5 is also possible and similar in nature. } 11. O-O-O a5
{ This is a fine move, but White may force a draw if he knows/finds the main line given here. If you expect this to happen and want to avoid it: Bd7 is a playable alternative, leading to sharp play. }
12. f4 a4
{ Important to remember. This is the most active move, avoiding a Knight retreat. }
13. fxe5 axb3 14. exf6 bxa2
{ wins for Black. White's king position is to shaky. } *

