1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nf3
{ By far the most popular way here to avoid the Benko. Alternatives are rather harmless. }
3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6
{ This position may also arise from 1 c4 c5 or 1 Nf3 c5 2 c4. Therefore knowing the lines presented here might be a good starting point to build a repertoire vs. the English Opening. }
5. Nc3 e6
{ This is the best move here. g6 is the main alternative, but 6 e4 leads to the Maroczy Bind which is as far from the spirit of the Benko as you can imagine. Our move leads to lively piece play and more active chances for Black. }
6. g3 Qb6
{ This is an important part of Black's concept. He puts pressure on White's centralized Knight, forcing a commitment. }
