[Round "?"]
[White "1 d4 Nf6 2 c4 c5 White avoids 3 d5"]
[Black "1 d4 Nf6 2 c4 c5 White avoids 3 d5 #31"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. e3 g6
{ This the most Benko-style move. If you like you may also play 3.... cxd4 4 exd4 d5, which surprisingly transposes into a Caro-Kann Panov line. If you have some knowledge there it's a way to go. }
4. Nc3 Bg7 5. d5
{ White goes into a Benoni with the rather tame move e3 being played. This can hardly be critical for Black, but it leads to a position type we don't play usually. }
5... O-O 6. Nf3 d6 7. Be2 e6 8. O-O Re8 9. Nd2 Na6 10. e4 Nc7
{ A setup like this is my recommendation. Delaying exd5 does not give White the c4 square for the Knight. Black still can play for a later b5. }
