[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "White Declines the Gambit"]
[Black "Benko Gambit White Declines the Gambit #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Nf3 Bb7
{ This move is my recommendation. I have to admit that before studying the details I never quite got the ideas behind the move. Black basically prepares to take on c4 under the correct circumstances, followed by . ..e6 to break White's centre. This is usually happening if White neglects control of d5 with moves like Nbd2 or Qc2. After 5 a4, which is the main move, the play gets quite 'un-Benko-like', but the position is fine for Black. }
5. a4
{ The most popular line. White forces a commitment on the queenside. Black now needs to close this side of the board, leading to a tough strategic fight. }
5... Qa5+ 6. Bd2 { The only move basically. } 6... b4
{ Compared with b4 the moves Bd2 and Qa5 are inserted. This is slightly favorable for Black, as White's development is rather clogged up and the Queen often goes back to c7. Also note that White would have liked to play b3 and Bb2 in this kind of structure, but this now almost impossible to get in. }
7. g3 d6
{ Is going to to be very similar to 7 Qc2 of the illustrative game Leitao-Felgaer. }
*

