[White "White Declines the Gambit"]
[Black "Benko Gambit White Declines the Gambit #18"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Nf3 Bb7
{ This move is my recommendation. I have to admit that before studying the details I never quite got the ideas behind the move. Black basically prepares to take on c4 under the correct circumstances, followed by . ..e6 to break White's centre. This is usually happening if White neglects control of d5 with moves like Nbd2 or Qc2. After 5 a4, which is the main move, the play gets quite 'un-Benko-like', but the position is fine for Black. }
5. Qc2 { White prepares to play e4 to support the centre. } 5... bxc4 6. e4 e6
{ The key concept. Black needs to make his Bishop count, breaking the bind by the d5 pawn. }
7. dxe6 dxe6
{ Very important ! In this line with 4 Nf3 Bb7 Black always retakes on e6 with the d-pawn. This provides Black with a healthy structure on the kingside. The c5 pawn is useful to control d4 and not weak at all at the moment. }
8. Nc3 Nc6 9. Bxc4 Be7 10. O-O Nd4
{ This is a nice square for the Knight. White will take it at some point, most likely immediately. }
11. Nxd4 cxd4 12. Rd1 Qb6 13. Na4 Qc6 14. Rxd4 Nxe4
{ And all works out fine for us. } *

