1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. a4
{ White declines the Gambit and forces the situation on the queenside. Black now has a fundamental choice between a more open or a closed position. I think it is mostly a matter of taste. I'll look at the 'open variation' here because I think it probably suits most Benko fans better. }
4... bxc4 5. Nc3 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Bxc4 Bg7 8. f4 O-O 9. Nf3 Ba6
{ This bishop is usually quite useless in many Benoni/Benko structures - exchanging it makes sense. }
10. Qe2 Bxc4 11. Qxc4 Nbd7 12. O-O Rb8 13. Qe2 Rb4
{ Black has good pressure here while White looks somewhat overextended. } *

