1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Nf3 { Informational line: } 4... g6
{ This is the most Benko like move. However I noticed a transpositional problem that I couldn't solve. }
5. cxb5 a6 6. e3
{ Now play will transpose to the line 1 d4 Nf6 2 c4 c5 3 d5 b5 4 cxb5 a6 5 e3, with Black being committed to a g6 setup. I tried hard, but I did not find a good solution to the following line. }
6... Bg7
{ axb5 is recommended in the Benko book by S.V. Pedersen, but that line does not work at all upon closer inspection. Black has nothing better than playing along the 5 e3 g6 lines. }
7. Nc3 O-O 8. a4 { And it transposes as mentioned. } 8... Bb7 9. Ra3 e6 10.
dxe6 fxe6 11. Be2
{ Stockfish gives White a huge edge here and I couldn't prove otherwise. 11 Qd6 is also not easy at all to tackle. }
*

