[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "White takes b5, but not a6"]
[Black "Benko Gambit White takes b5, but not a6 #17"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. b6
{ This is one of the most respectable ways of declining the gambit. Black has to be precise to get a good game. }
5... Qxb6
{ Taking the pawn to continue with a later ...g6 is the most Benko-like approach. }
6. Nc3 d6 7. e4 g6 8. Nf3 Bg7 9. Nd2
{ This position also arises frequently with Nd2 first and only then e4 to avoid any Bg4 options. }
9... O-O
{ Over the next few moves White will play Be2, Nc4, O-O and a4, possibly a5. He may choose various move orders, but Black's setup is identical in all cases. We will play Nbd7, Rb8 and will return to d8 with the Queen if attacked or even voluntarily, as b6 is often needed for the Nd7 to jump to. A Knight on c4 should be challenged with said Knight to b6. An additional idea is Nf6-e8-c7. This is in particular desirable after White has played a4-a5, allowing Knight to b5. As usual it is a good idea to trade the c8-Bishop, but it is not easy to achieve. a6-a5 in order to play Ba6 is one way that works in some cases. Some words on the Queen's retreat square d8: others are possible and not THAT bad, but I feel d8 makes a lot of sense. The Queen protects e7 in case of Bg5 and does not occupy a square usually needed for a minor piece  (like c7 for a Knight)  . }
10. Be2 Nbd7 11. Nc4 Qd8
{ Again back to d8 ! Now 12 O-O or a4 will transpose to positions examined via other move orders. This is not all that important as long as you understand the setup for Black. }
*

