[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. e3
{ This modest looking move is actually quite ambitious. White wants to keep the pawn on b5, supporting it with a later a4. Of course e3 also prepares development of the kingside. }
5... axb5
{ This is Black's most forcing continuation, giving him decent play. I checked some alternatives and have to state that 5 e3 is a quite dangerous move. }
6. Bxb5 Qa5+ 7. Nc3 Bb7
{ Black immediately puts pressure on the d5 pawn. White can't hold the pawn, but will get some good development that forces Black to be precise. }
8. Bd2
{ This breaks the pin and basically forces the black queen back because any threats against d5 are useless with the discovery of the Nc3 being imminent. }
8... Qb6 9. Nf3 Nxd5
{ So Black has got the pawn back and some centre pawns - however the development does not look good at all. It's very important to be precise here.  This is the clearly most popular line, but I think 10 a4 is actually more critical. }
10. a4 e6 11. O-O Be7 12. e4
{ This move is extremely tough to meet. One misstep and you're toast ! Black is behind in development and a mistake is costly. It has to be mentioned that this is a very rare line in practice, it shows up only twice on my database, so it's not very likely that you are going to meet it in every other game. }
12... Nb4 { I think this needs to be played. } 13. Bf4
{ This is clearly the best move for White. On other moves Black will castle and be ok. }
13... Qd8
{ I know that it looks strange, but there is a rationale. Black needs to castle badly and this move makes it possible. }
14. Bxb8 Rxb8 15. Ne5 Bc8
{ Retro, but good. Black will castle and then get rid of the Knight on e5. } *

