[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. f3
{ This move is quite aggressive. White intends to build up a pawn chain with e4 coming. It is essential to know a concrete reply here, just playing stereotypical moves like ...g6 does not suffice. }
5... axb5 6. e4
{ Now Black only has one playable move as e4-e5 is threatened and d7-d6 would drop b5 with check. }
6... Qa5+ 7. b4
{ Wow, quite a brutal move ! White has not yet developed a single piece and still lashes out. }
7... cxb4
{ Taking with the Queen is possible, but cxb4 is just fine for Black, so I don't see the need to check the tricky Queen capture. }
8. Nd2 e6 9. Nb3 Qb6
{ A very unconventional position. Black is fine in my opinion. } 10. Ne2 Na6
11. Ned4 Nc5 12. Qe2 Qb8
{ and Black is better. This move is not very obvious, but it is strong. It mostly avoids issues on the g1-a7 diagonal if White goes Be3. Also controlling b8-h2 is useful, sometimes even allowing ...Bd6. }
*

