10. a3
{ The main move, trying to open up the queenside quickly. Note that Ba5 may cause havoc if Black takes it. }
10... e6
{ Extremely important move ! Taking on a3 instead leads to immediate disaster ! }
11. dxe6 Bxe6 12. Ne3
{ This is better than taking on b4. White prepares to development the f1 Bishop after all. }
12... d5
{ This is the most principled and logical move. White has the option to play a long, forced line after it to force a perpetual at the end. If you strongly fear that might happen and a draw is unacceptable you may play bxa3, which is trickier for Black than d5, but avoids a forced draw. }
13. Bb5+ Bd7 14. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 15. exd5 Be7
{ The d5 pawn will fall to Nb6, giving Black at least equality. } *

