1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. bxa6 g6 6. Nc3 Bg7
{ This move has brought the Benko Gambit back on the map. Some years ago Black was suffering severly in the Main line Benko Accepted, so alternatives were needed quite badly. This new approach, starting with Bg7, is named after the Serbian GM Perunovic, who contributed a lot to its development. }
7. Nf3 O-O 8. g3
{ The Fianchetto system is a serious option for White against the traditional system with Bxa6. Here, with Black having delayed the capture, it is a far less dangerous approach as we will see. Instead of 8 g3 White may also transpose to the main lines with 8 e4 or 8 a7 Rxa7 9 e4. }
8... d6 9. Bg2 Nbd7 10. O-O Nb6 11. Ne1 Bxa6 12. Nc2 Ng4
{ This way to activate the Knight is not availabe usually in the e4 based setups, but here it is seen very frequently. }
13. h3 Ne5 14. b3 Nf3+ 15. Bxf3 Bxc3 16. Rb1 Bc8
{ Again an important trick. h3 and a2 are hanging ! Black is fine. } *

