[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. bxa6 g6 6. Nc3 Bg7
{ This move has brought the Benko Gambit back on the map. Some years ago Black was suffering severly in the Main line Benko Accepted, so alternatives were needed quite badly. This new approach, starting with Bg7, is named after the Serbian GM Perunovic, who contributed a lot to its development. }
7. e4
{ The main move and the traditional reason why Bg7 was not viewed as a serious move some years ago. }
7... O-O 8. Nf3 Qa5 9. Bd2 Bxa6 10. Be2
{ This seems more testing than taking on a6. } 10... d6 11. O-O Bxe2 12. Qxe2
Qa6 { This is essential. Other moves don't work nearly as well. } 13. Qd1
{ Doesn't look all that frightening, but Qc2 is a good idea for White to organize his position. }
13... Nbd7 14. Qc2 Rfb8 15. a4
{ White tries to set up the dreaded a4/Nb5 configuration. Black needs to fight that idea, it is the most dangerous one White has up his sleeve. }
15... Rb4
{ Now 16.Nb5 can be answered with 16...Rxa4, when 17.Nc7 would force a draw. If you need to avoid that and feel your opponent will end the game like that you need to deviate with 15...Qc4 or 15...Ne8, which are also playable. ! }
16. Rfe1 Ng4 { This is more fighting than Qc4. } 17. Ra3 Nde5 18. Nxe5 Nxe5 19.
b3 c4 { And Black regains the pawn with good play. } *

