[White "White takes b5 and a6"]
[Black "White takes b5 and a6 #58"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. bxa6 g6 6. Nc3 Bg7
{ This move has brought the Benko Gambit back on the map. Some years ago Black was suffering severly in the Main line Benko Accepted, so alternatives were needed quite badly. This new approach, starting with Bg7, is named after the Serbian GM Perunovic, who contributed a lot to its development. }
7. e4
{ The main move and the traditional reason why Bg7 was not viewed as a serious move some years ago. }
7... O-O 8. Be2 { This is trying to improve on 8 Nf3. } 8... Qa5 9. Bd2 Bxa6
10. e5
{ The idea behind 8 Be2 compared to 8 Nf3. Now Black is forced back to e8. }
10... Ne8 11. Nf3 d6 12. e6 Bxe2 13. Qxe2 Qa6
{ Note that White's d5 pawn is a long term target, even in the endgame. } 14.
exf7+ Rxf7 15. Nb5 { Not the most obvious move, but it threatens Ng5. } 15...
Qb7 16. O-O Qxd5 17. Nc3 Bxc3
{ That is forced unfortunately, but Black is still OK I think. } 18. Bxc3 Nc6
{ This Bishop on c3 looks scary, but Black should get in e7-e5 followed by Nd4 to blunt it. It's an interesting position with equal chances. }
*

