1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 c5 3. Bxf6 gxf6 4. d5 f5 5. c4 Bg7 6. Nc3 d6 7. Qc2
{ 7.e3  b5 !?  Is the main recommendation given in the repertoire. Qc2 avoids this possibility. }
7... O-O 8. e3 e6
{ Attacking the centre. We will see the concept behind it soon. } 9. Rd1
{ This delays castling. There were some interesting alternatives.   9.Bd3  Nd7  10.Nf3  Ne5  11.Nxe5  dxe5 !?  Not forced, but quite enterprising.  12.O-O-O  e4  13.Be2  Qa5  This is quite unclear and interesting to play for sure.   9.O-O-O  Na6  10.a3  Nc7  11.Nge2  b5  with great complications that are tough to assess.  12.dxe6  fxe6  13.cxb5  d5  looks very scary for White. }
9... a6 { That looks like a slow move, but it is very ambitious. } 10. Nge2
{ 10.Nh3  This would have been aimed at preventing b5 or at least make it less effective.  e5   10...Qe7  11.Be2  b5 !?  12.cxb5  axb5  13.Bxb5  Na6  This is certainly quite playable for Black as well.  11.Be2  b5  12.cxb5  axb5  13.Bxb5  Qh4  Again with interesting play for Black. }
10... b5 { Breaking open the game, based on the g7 monster Bishop. } 11. cxb5
{ 11.Nf4  White tries to develop the kingside after all.  b4  12.Nce2  e5  13.Nh5  Bh6  14.Neg3  f4  15.Nf5  Qg5  16.Nxh6+  Qxh6  17.Be2  fxe3  18.fxe3  f5  And Black is fine after this quite long, but logical sequence of moves. }
11... axb5 12. Nxb5
{ White decides to grab the pawn, but now gets under fire quickly. } 12... exd5
13. Nec3
{ 13.Rxd5  Rxa2  14.Nec3  Be6  15.Rd1  Qa5  And White is under pressure. }
13... Be6 14. Nxd5
{ 14.Be2  Nc6  15.O-O  d4  Also doesn't feel like fun for White, but better than getting wiped out as it happened in the actual game. }
14... Bxd5 15. Rxd5 Rxa2 16. Nc3 Qa5
{ And here White is already completely lost. Rxb2 is a terrible threat. } 17.
Kd1 Ra1+ 18. Ke2 Nc6 19. Rd2 Nd4+ 20. exd4 cxd4 21. Nb1 Bh6
{ Not a good day at the office for the white player, being a 2644 GM and now not having a single decently placed piece. }
22. Kf3 Qd5+ 23. Kg3 Rxb1
{ This is missing a direct win. It's quite possible that both players had time problems here.   23...f4+  24.Kg4  Kh8  is already a forced mate. }
24. Qxb1 Bxd2 25. Qd1 Qe4
{ 25...f4+  26.Kh4  Ba5  27.Qf3  And White is not getting mated and still fighting. }
26. h4 { 26.Qf3  Would have still put up stuff resistance. } 26... Qf4+ 27. Kh3
Qxf2 28. g3
{ And here the database gives 0-1, and indeed 28... f4 wins for Black convincingly. A game that shows the ideas in this structure very nicely. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Illustrative Games"]
[Black "Nielsen, Peter Heine vs. Pedersen, Nicolai Vesterbek"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ Note that the White player, Peter Heine Nielsen, is probably the world's leading Chess theoretician and current second to the World Champion Magnus Carlsen. Before working with the highest rated player of all time Peter Heine was the second to Vishy Anand, making him one of if not the best prepared player for years. }
1... Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 b5 4. c4 g6 5. cxb5 a6 6. b6
{ For details on the early moves of this game please check the repertoire itself. }
6... Qxb6 7. Nc3 d6 8. e4 Bg7 9. Nd2 O-O 10. Be2 Nbd7 11. Nc4 Qc7
{ 11...Qd8  This setup is my choice for the repertoire. I think the Queen is best here, as it allows Nc7 and covers e7, which may come in handy after a later Bg5. }
12. Bf4 Rb8 { A useful move that Black almost invariably plays. } 13. Qd2
{ This is not working well due to a devilish tactical blow.   13.O-O  This is the more critical continuation.  Nb6  14.Ne3  This is the moment when you rather want your Queen on d8, as you like to play Ne8-c7. }
13... Nb6 { Not yet the blow, but hang on... } 14. Ne3
{ The move that White wants to play, avoiding trades. It fails to the mentioned tactic !   14.O-O  This was mandatory.  Nxc4  15.Bxc4  Bd7  With Bb5 to come Black is fine. }
14... Na4
{ This move should be played exactly when the White player is holding his mug of coffee to test his reaction ! What a blow... }
15. Nxa4
{ Other moves don't help much.   15.Ned1  Nxc3  16.Nxc3  Nxe4  17.Nxe4  Rxb2  18.Qe3  Qa5+  19.Kf1  Bd4  20.Qc1  Rxe2  21.Kxe2  Qb5+  22.Ke1  Bxa1  23.Qxa1  Qb4+  24.Kf1  Qxe4  25.Bh6  f6  26.Bxf8  Bh3  27.Rg1  Qd3+  28.Ke1  Bg4  29.f3  Qe3+  30.Kf1  Bf5  And here White will probably resign.   15.Qc2  Nxc3  16.bxc3  Nxe4  And that's it. }
15... Nxe4 16. Qc2 Qa5+ 17. Kf1 Rb4
{ This is the big point ! White has loose pieces on the 4th rank. } 18. Nc4
{ probably the toughest try.   18.Nc3 ?  Nxc3  19.bxc3  Rxf4  is easy.   18.Bc4 ?  Qxa4  19.Qxe4  Bf5  20.Nxf5  Rxc4  and Black wins. }
18... Qxa4 19. Qxe4 Bf5 20. Qxe7
{ 20.Qe3  Rxc4  21.b3  Re4  22.bxa4  Rxe3  23.Bxe3  Bxa1  24.Bxa6  Rb8  And Black wins easily. }
20... Re8 21. Qxd6 Bxb2
{ This is enough to win, the computer improvement has some points hard to figure out for a human player.   21...Rxc4 !  This is the most forceful way of finishing things.  22.b3   22.Bxc4  Qxc4+  23.Kg1  Bxb2  24.Rd1   24.Rf1  Qxf1+  25.Kxf1  Bd3+  26.Kg1  Re1#  is a nice end to the game :-  24...Qd3 !  And the White rook has no square, as Rf1 loses as seen before.  25.Rf1  Qxf1+  26.Kxf1  Bd3+  27.Kg1  Re1#  22...Qb4  23.Bxc4  Bxa1  24.Be3  Bd4  25.Qf4  Qc3  And Black wins quickly. }
22. Nxb2 Rxb2 23. Be3
{ 23.Kg1  Rbxe2  24.h3  Qd4  25.Rf1  Be4  26.Kh2  Qxd5  27.Qxd5  Bxd5  And Black should win, but the game continues. }
23... Rxe2 24. Kxe2 Qc4+ 25. Ke1 Qc3+ 26. Ke2 Bg4+ 27. f3 Qxe3+
{ 27...Rxe3+  28.Kf2  Rxf3+  Also leads to mate. } 28. Kf1 Bf5 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Illustrative Games"]
[Black "Radjabov, Teimour vs. Gelfand, Boris"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ Note the move order of this game. We would reach this from a declined Benko with 3 Nf3. Having this line in your repertoire can easily be a good start for a repertoire versus the English opening. }
5. Nc3 e6 6. g3 Qb6 7. Nb3
{ 7.Ndb5  As discussed in the Repertoire section this seems to be more critical for Black. }
7... Ne5 8. e4 Bb4 9. Qe2 d6 10. f4
{ 10.Bd2  This keeps the structure intact, but should also be fine for Black. }
10... Nc6
{ 10...Bxc3+ ?  That must be avoided ! Black should wait with taking on c3 until Be3 is played.  11.bxc3  Nc6  12.Ba3 !  is very awkward for Black. }
11. Be3 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Qc7 13. Bg2 e5
{ This is a good decision. There are alternatives, but this is easy to handle and gives Black good play with a sound structure. }
14. c5 { 14.O-O  b6  is the issue, with White having even more weaknesses. }
14... b6
{ Simple and good. The arising pawn structure is fine for Black and White has little dynamic compensation. }
15. cxd6
{ 15.cxb6  axb6  Isn't any better. Note that Ba6 is an additional option now. }
15... Qxd6 16. O-O O-O 17. f5
{ A centralizing move like this was better, still being quite OK for White.   17.Rad1  Qc7  18.Rd2  Bb7  19.Rc1  Going for c4-c5. I rather take Black, but White is still in the game of course. }
17... Rd8 18. Rfd1 Qa3
{ The queen is well placed there ! It attacks the weaknesses and prepares a possible Ba6. }
19. Rxd8+
{ 19.Bg5  Ba6  20.c4  Rac8  21.Bxf6  gxf6  22.Qg4+  Kf8  The capture on f6 is not dangerous at all. Note that the White minor pieces are completely harmless and ineffective. }
19... Nxd8 20. Bg5
{ 20.g4  Ba6  21.c4  Ne8  Going for d6 later. The White pawns are not yet dangerous at all, while the weaknesses are felt. }
20... Ba6 21. Qd2 Qe7 22. Rd1
{ 22.Bf1  is also completely prospectless for White.  Bxf1  23.Rxf1  Nb7  24.Kg2  Rd8  25.Qe2  Qc7  And White will fall apart in the long run. There are 3 weaknesses to defend  (a2, c3 and e4)  . That's too much. }
22... Nb7 23. Bf3 Rd8 24. Qc1 Rxd1+ 25. Bxd1 Nd6 26. Bxf6 gxf6 27. Qe3 Qc7 28.
a4 Qd7 29. a5 Nxe4 30. Bc2 Qb5 31. Qf3 Ng5 32. Qg2 bxa5
{ An excellent achivement by Gelfand, showing the potential of this line. On a sidenote: I was present in London when this game was played. It was a delight to have Gelfand in the analysis room to explain the game to the audience. I remembered this game when I was looking to complete the repertoire with an option versus 1 d4 Nf6 2 c4 c5 3 Nf3. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Illustrative Games"]
[Black "Garza Marco, Sergio vs. Vallejo Pons, Francisco"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. bxa6 g6 6. Nc3 Bxa6
{ Back in 2009 Vallejo still played the 'old main line' instead of the Perunovic. In recent games he has switched like almost all Benko fans. }
7. Nf3 d6 8. g3 Bg7 9. Bg2 Nbd7 10. O-O
{ 10.Rb1 !  This is a tricky line that has posed Black problems for years. We don't need to worry about it as our move order prevents this possibility - see the Repertoire for details. }
10... Nb6 11. Re1 O-O
{ This position is part of our repertoire via the Perunovic move order - while having sidestepped the 10 Rb1 ! line.. }
12. e4 Nfd7
{ One key issue for White in the Fianchetto Benko are the light squares after having played the e-pawn. d3 is quite weak and Bf1 only trades the Bishop which does not help to fix this issue. }
13. Qc2
{ White tries to develop his queenside.This simple sounding task is in fact not all that easy to accomplish. Qc2 covers the Knight so that b2-b3 becomes an option in the future. }
13... Nc4 14. Bg5
{ 14.b3 ?  A common mistake that is punished immediately.  Qa5 !  is already losing for White ! }
14... h6 15. Bf4 Qa5 { White needs to be very careful here. } 16. Rac1
{ 16.Rab1 ?  Nxb2  is a standard tactic. } 16... g5 17. Be3
{ 17.Bd2  This is probably better, but also rather unattractive for White. For just a pawn he has to defend to stay in the game.  Rfb8  This is Black's standard setup in the Fianchetto Benko  (usually without h6/g5, but just with g6)  . He has enormous pressure.  18.b3  Nxd2  19.Qxd2  c4  20.bxc4   20.Nd4 ?  Whenever you play c5-c4 in the Benko make sure to check if White manages to get a Knight to c6 !  Bxd4  21.Qxd4  cxb3  22.axb3  Rxb3  And White is in danger of falling apart very quickly. The slightly weakened Black kingside plays no role at all.  20...Bxc4  21.h4  g4  22.Nd4  Bxd4  23.Qxd4  Ne5  White is still under some pressure. It is not easy for him to coordinate.  24.Qe3  Kg7  25.Ne2  Bxe2  26.Rxe2  Qa3  27.Rc3  Rb1+  28.Kh2  Qa5  29.f4  gxf3  30.Bxf3  Qb4  31.a3  Qa5  32.Rb3  Rxb3  33.Qxb3  Qxa3  34.Qxa3  Rxa3  35.Bh5  A very long line that shows some typical play. Black regains the pawn and enjoys the slightly better endgame. }
17... Rfb8 18. b3 Nxe3
{ 18...Nce5  Also quite logical.  19.Nxe5   19.Red1 ?  Nxf3+  20.Bxf3  Bxc3  21.Qxc3  Qxa2  is clearly better for Black who will be a pawn UP soon.  19...Nxe5  20.Red1  In order to be better White would need to trade light squared Bishops, play a4 and then manage Nb5. This is never going to happen - Black's pressure is too irritating.  Qa3   20...c4 !?  This is also quite thematic.  21.Ne2  Nd3  22.Rb1  cxb3  23.axb3  Nb4  24.Qd2  Bd3  25.Rbc1  Bxe2  26.Qxe2  Na2  27.h4  Nxc1  28.Rxc1  gxh4  29.Qg4  Black won the exchange, but this is rather unclear. White has got some fine play on the kingside.  21.Rb1  g4  22.Qd2  Kh7  Black has enough compensation for sure, but it is not clear how to progress. On the other hand I can't imagine that White has much fun here either. }
19. Rxe3 Bd4 20. Ree1 Ne5 21. Nxe5
{ 21.Red1  Nxf3+  This starts a forced sequence to get the pawn back.  22.Bxf3  Bxc3  23.Qxc3  Qxa2  24.Rb1  c4  25.Rb2  Rxb3  26.Rxa2  Rxc3  27.Be2  Bb7  28.Rxa8+  Bxa8  29.Rb1  Rb3  30.Ra1  Bb7  31.Bxc4  Rb4  32.Bd3  g4  and Black is still able to ask White some questions in this endgame. }
21... Bxe5 22. Kh1
{ This allows Black to get a large advantage. It's not easy to play such a position.   22.Nb1  This seems to defend quite well.  c4  23.Nd2  cxb3  24.axb3  Rc8  25.Nc4  Bxc4  26.bxc4  Rcb8  27.Re2  Rb2  28.Qd1  Rxe2  29.Qxe2  Qa2  30.Qxa2  Rxa2  31.Rd1  Bc3  32.Bf3  Bb4  33.Kf1  Bc5  34.Be2  g4  with a draw to come.   22.Qd2  Qb4   22...Bc8  This regains the pawn with equal play.  23.Bf1  Bxc3  24.Rxc3  Qxa2  25.Qe3  Ra3  26.Bc4  Qb2  27.h4  Ra1  28.Rxa1  Qxa1+  29.Kg2  gxh4  30.gxh4  Kh7  and it is equal.  23.Rc2  c4  24.bxc4  Bxc4  White should hold with perfect play, but it is not easy at all for him. }
22... c4
{ 22...Bxc3 !  This was even better.  23.Qxc3  Qxa2  Double attacking b3 and f2.  24.Re3  Qxf2  25.Rc2  Qf6  26.Qxf6  exf6  27.Rf2  Bc8  28.Rxf6  Ra1+  29.Rf1  Rxf1+  30.Bxf1  Kg7  31.Kg1  Bd7  And Black has a substantial edge. The pawns are weak and Black is more active. }
23. bxc4 Rc8 24. Bf1
{ 24.f4  This weakens White's position, but might be still possible.  Bd4  25.Bf1  Bxc4  26.Qd2  Bg7  27.Bg2  Bxd5 !  28.Qxd5  Bxc3  29.Qxa5  Rxa5  30.Re3  Rac5  Black is better, but White has good drawing chances for sure. }
24... Bxc4 25. Nb1
{ 25.Bh3  Rc5  26.f4  Bf6  27.Bg2  Bxd5 !  And Black should win here as well. }
25... Bxd5 26. Qe2 Be6
{ White's position is in complete disarray. It just takes some moves to take him apart. }
27. a3 Rab8 28. Kg1 Rb2 29. Qe3 Rcb8 30. Red1 R8b3 31. Qe1 Qxe1 32. Rxe1 Bd4
33. Be2 Bg4 34. Nc3 Rxc3 *

