[White "Illustrative Games"]
[Black "Babujian, Levon vs. Andriasian, Zaven"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. bxa6 g6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 O-O 8. e4
Qa5 9. Bd2 Bxa6 10. Bxa6 Qxa6 11. Qe2 e6 12. Qxa6 Nxa6 13. dxe6 fxe6 14. O-O
Nb4
{ The moves up to here have been discussed in the repertoire. Let's see how the game continued. I selected this game because it illustrates how Black's play continues even after the Queen trade. Note that in the Benko trading Queens quite often is no issue for Black at all. In more traditional gambits often the King is the primary target - so you keep Queens on. In the Benko you might get an attack on the King as well if White misplays it badly - but usually it is about pressure on the queenside where Queens are not essential most of the time. }
15. b3
{ 15.a4  Nd3  16.a5  'Passed pawns must be pushed'. This leads to forced play that will often fizzle out at the end.   16.Rab1  Played in Zhao,X  (2510)  -Javakhishvili,L  (2487)  Chengdu 2016.  d5  17.exd5  exd5 !  This gives Black a very nice position. It's not easy to play White here.  In the mentioned game   17...Nxd5 ?!  was played.  18.Ng5  Rfe8  19.Nge4  Nxc3  20.bxc3  Rxa4  21.f3  and White was slightly better due to the sounder pawn structure and went on to win a long game.  18.Ne1 !  This seems to be best.   18.Bg5  d4  19.Bxf6  Rxf6  20.Ne4  Re6  21.Rfd1  Rxe4  22.Rxd3  Rxa4  Black is slightly better.   18.b3  d4  19.Nb5  Ne4  Black is a lot better here already.  20.Rbd1  Nb2  21.Rb1  Nxa4 !  22.bxa4  Rxf3  23.gxf3  Nxd2  24.Nc7  Rc8  25.Nd5  Rd8  And Black should win with his passers.  18...Nxe1  19.Rfxe1  d4  20.Nb5  Rxa4  21.Nc7  Rb8  22.Ne6  Bf8  This is around equal, even though it is still rather White who needs to be careful.  16...Nxb2  17.a6  d5  18.Ra2  Nc4  19.exd5  exd5  20.Bg5   20.Rb1  d4  21.Nb5  Rfb8  22.a7  Rb6  23.Kf1  Nd6  24.Rab2  Nxb5  25.Rxb5  Rxb5  26.Rxb5  Rxa7  27.Rxc5  Ne4  again with equality.  20...d4  21.Bxf6  Rxf6  22.Ne4  Rfxa6  23.Rxa6  Rxa6  24.Nxc5  Ra5  25.Nd3  With equal play.   15.e5  Ng4  16.Ne4  Nd3  17.Bc3  Forced after 15 e5. Now Black has some options.  Ra4   17...Rxf3 !?  18.gxf3  Ngxe5  19.Rfd1  c4  Black is a full exchange down, but it seems playable.  20.Nd6  Nxf3+  21.Kg2  Nh4+  22.Kg3  Nf5+  23.Nxf5  gxf5  24.Bxg7  Kxg7  25.a4  d5  26.b3  Nb2  27.Rd4  cxb3  28.Rb4  Kf6  29.Rxb3  Nxa4  Black should hold here. I still have some doubt about the sac though.   17...c4  18.Nd6  Ngxe5  19.Nxe5  Bxe5  20.Bxe5  Nxe5  21.f4  Nd3  22.Nxc4  d5  23.Ne5  Nxb2  With an equal endgame.  18.Rad1  Nxb2 !   18...c4 ?  This was played in Komljenovic,D  (2405)  -Trent,L  (2469)  Jaen 2014  19.b3  Rxa2  20.bxc4  Nf4 ?   20...Ndxe5  21.Bxe5  Nxe5  22.Nxe5  Bxe5  23.Rxd7  Ra4  24.Ng5  Rxc4  25.Nxe6  And Black is pawn down for no compensation. Still this is what he should have played objectively.  21.Ng3 ??   21.Bb4  Rfa8  22.Rxd7  And White is close to winning.  21...Nxg2 !  now BLACK is winning instead !  22.Ng5   22.Kxg2  Ne3+  23.Kg1  Nxf1  and Black wins even more easily than in the game.  22...h6  23.N5e4  Nh4   23...Nf4 !  was even more convincing.  24.Rxd7  Nf3+  25.Kg2 ?  Ne3+  And Lawrence Trent won quickly.  19.Bxb2  Rxe4  20.Rxd7  Bxe5  21.Nxe5  Nxe5  22.Bxe5  Rxe5  23.g3  This should end in a draw.   15.Rfd1  Nd3  This is a rather forcing move. White only has one good move now.   15...d5  This has been tested in practical play as well. It is fine for Black, as is Nd3 on move 15.  16.exd5   16.Ng5  Ra6  17.Nb5  A quite typical computer line. Very direct, but it seems to hold for Black.  Nxe4  18.Nc7  Bxb2  19.Nxe4   19.Bxb4  Rc6 !  Wow ! It all works, just about !  20.Nxe4  cxb4  21.Nxd5  exd5  22.Rab1  Rc2  23.Rxd5  Re8  24.f3  Ra8  And it holds for Black again.  19...Bxa1  20.Rxa1  Rc6  21.Nxc5  Rxc5  22.Nxe6  Rc2  23.Nxf8  Rxd2  24.Ne6  Rxa2  And a draw again !  16...exd5  17.Nb5  Played in Lombaers, P  (2289)  -Damaso,R  (2447)  Porto 2016.   17.Bg5  Ne4 !  18.Nxe4   18.Be3 ?!  Bxc3  19.bxc3  Nc2  20.Rac1  Rxa2  And White is struggling to hold. He probably manages, but it's not nice to play.  18...dxe4  19.Nd2  Bxb2  20.Rab1  Rxa2  21.Nxe4  Bd4  This should end in a draw, but there are still some ideas in the position due to the c-pawn.  17...Ne4 !?   17...Rxa2  18.Rxa2  Nxa2  19.Ra1  Nb4  also leads to equality, but is easier for White to play.  18.Bxb4  cxb4  19.Nbd4  Ra6  Black's active pieces make it impossible foe White to think about converting a pawn.In fact White is probably quite happy here if he finds a clear line to return the pawn and force some draw.  20.a4 ?!   20.a3  Rfa8  21.Rd3  g5  22.h3  h5  23.Rad1  This is a rather safe way for White to get out of the game with half a point.  20...g5 !  21.h3  h5  22.h4 ?!   22.Nc2  is the engine move and probably sufficient for a draw.  g4  23.Nxb4  Rd6  24.Rxd5  Rxd5  25.Nxd5  gxf3  26.a5  and we can stop here - a draw is very likely.  22...g4  23.Ng5  Nxf2  24.Nde6 ??   24.Rd2  Ne4  25.Nxe4  dxe4  26.Nb3  e3  27.Re2  Not very attractive for White, but it was mandatory to play it.  24...Nxd1  25.Nxf8  Kxf8   25...Bd4+  26.Kh2  Nxb2  was even cleaner, but the game move is enough.  26.Rxd1  Bxb2  27.Rxd5  Rxa4 ?   27...b3 !  28.Kf2 ?   28.Rb5 !  still was tough for Black to win after he had missed some knockouts.  28...Bc1  29.Ne4  b3  30.Nc3  Rc4  31.Nb1  Bf4  32.Rxh5  Rc2+  33.Ke1  Rc1+  34.Ke2  Rxb1  35.Rf5+  Ke7  36.Rxf4  b2  37.Re4+  Kf6  and White resigned after what most likely was a time trouble fight at the end.  16.Bh6 !   16.Rab1  Ng4  was awkward for White in Urkedal,F  (2517)  -Lokander,M  (2365)  Stockholm 2015.  17.Rf1 ?   17.Be3 !  c4  18.Bd4  Bxd4  19.Nxd4  Ngxf2  was a better defence, but this is not easy to assess without engine help.  17...Bd4  18.Nxd4  cxd4  19.Nb5   19.Nd1  was tougher, but who plays such an ugly move ?!  19...Rxf2  20.Rxf2  Ngxf2  21.e5  Ne4  Those Knights are terrorizing White to no end.  22.Bh6  Nxe5   22...Rxa2 !  23.Rf1  Ra8  24.Nxd4  Nxe5  And Nf7 is the key idea to win.  23.Re1  d5  24.Nxd4  Ng4  25.Bc1  Kf7  26.a3  e5  27.Nf3  Ke6  28.b4  Ngf2  29.Ng5+  Nxg5  30.Kxf2  Ne4+  31.Ke3  Rc8  32.Bb2  Nd6  33.Bc1  d4+  34.Kd2  Kd5  And White resigned. The centre pawn are unstoppable.   16.b3  d5  17.exd5  Nxd5  18.Nxd5  exd5  19.Rab1  Rxa2  And White still has to stop the c-pawn here.  16...Nxb2  17.Bxg7  Kxg7  18.Rd6  Nc4  19.Rdd1  Nb2  Black has a draw in hand.  20.Rd6  Nc4  21.Rdd1  It's tough to play for a win here.  e5  Not exactly nice, but stops e4-e5.  22.Nd2  Nxd2  23.Rxd2  Ra3  24.Rc1  Rb8  25.f3  Rb4  Black has no realistic winning chances here either.   15.Bg5  Nd3  16.Rab1  Rfb8  Instead ...c4 or ...Ng4 were also fine.  17.Bxf6 ?   17.b3  This is the only move, White's very strange move loses straightaway.  17...Bxf6  The queenside collapses now. What did the White player overlook ?  18.e5  Nxe5  19.Ne4  Nxf3+  20.gxf3  Bd4  21.a3  d5  22.Ng5  Ra6  23.Rfe1  e5  and Black won in Danner,G  (2381)  -Smith,A  (2480)  Kecskemet 2015. }
15... d5
{ 15...Ra3  This is a yet untested alternative to the obvious d5. It seems to be OK for Black as well.  16.h3  Rfa8  17.Rac1  Nd3   17...Nxa2  18.Nxa2  Rxa2  19.e5  Nd5  20.Rxc5  Rb8  21.Rb1  Ra7  22.Rc2  Rab7  This should hold as well, but Black has more comfortable ways to play.  18.Rcd1  d5  19.exd5  Nxd5  20.Ne4  Rxa2  This will fizzle out to a draw. After Ra3 there are of course a lot more lines possible, but 15... d5 already is fine for Black, so there is little need for more. }
16. exd5
{ 16.Ng5  Ra6  17.e5  A try for White to make it interesting.  Ng4  18.f4  Bh6  19.h3  Bxg5  20.hxg4  Bd8  Black is fine here I think. White's extra pawn plays no important role and Black's pieces are active, in particular the Knight. }
16... exd5
{ Black is playing for a win. He actually does not risk all that much.   16...Nfxd5  This already draws effortlessly.  17.Nxd5  exd5  18.Rac1  Rxa2  19.Rxc5  Rxf3  20.Bxb4  Rxb3  21.Rc8+  Kf7  22.Rc7+  Kg8 }
17. Ng5
{ 17.Rac1  Black now has a direct was to a drawish ending again. I am unsure if he has more.  Nxa2   17...Nd3  18.Rc2  Nb4  is another way to repeat.  18.Nxa2  Rxa2  19.Rxc5  Ne4  20.Ra5  Rxd2  21.Nxd2  Nxd2  22.Rd1  Ne4  23.Rdxd5  Rxf2  24.Rd8+  Rf8  25.Rxf8+  Bxf8  26.Rb5  Kf7  and a draw is very likely. }
17... Rfe8 18. Rae1 Nd3
{ 18...Rxe1  19.Rxe1  Nd3  20.Rd1  Ng4  21.Nxd5  Ngxf2  22.Rf1  Bd4  23.Be3  Bxe3  24.Nxe3  Rxa2  Black has gotten the pawn back and has equality. }
19. Rxe8+ Rxe8 20. a4
{ 20.f3  This is suggested by Stockfish.  c4  21.bxc4  dxc4  22.Rb1  h6  23.Nge4  Nxe4  24.Nxe4  Ra8  25.Kf1  g5  26.Rb6  Rxa2  27.Rc6  c3  28.Bxc3  Bxc3  29.Nxc3  Rf2+  30.Kg1  Rb2  And Black will draw this easily. }
20... d4 21. Nb5 Re2 22. Bc1
{ 22.Rd1  The not terribly intuitive engine suggestion.  Nxf2  23.Kf1  d3  24.Nc3  c4  25.Nxe2  Nxd1  26.bxc4  dxe2+  27.Kxe2  Nb2  28.a5  Nxc4  29.a6  Nd5  30.a7  And the engine claims this might be a draw, quite a headscratcher... }
22... h6 { 22...Nd5 !  was even stronger ! } 23. Nf3 Ne4 24. Ba3
{ 24.Na3 !  was still putting up resistance. } 24... Ra2
{ Now the big problem for White is the threat Nc3 ! There is no defence anymore. }
25. Ne1 Nxe1 26. Rxe1 d3 27. Kf1 Nd2+ 28. Kg1 Nxb3 29. Rd1 c4 30. Kf1 Nd2+ 31.
Ke1 Ne4 32. Kf1 Rxf2+ 33. Kg1 Ra2 34. a5 Nc3 35. Nxc3 Bxc3 36. Bc5 Rxa5 37. Be3
h5 38. Kf2 Ra1 39. Rxa1 Bxa1 40. Bc1 Bd4+ 41. Kf3 c3 42. Ba3 Kf7
{ The line examined in this game seems to be perfectly fine for him. Around move 15 White quite often should just take a draw by repetition or allow a forced line to a draw. It is very difficult to play White in a practical game. Note that White is a pawn up, but this pawn  (look at the h-pawn !)  does not play where the action is taking place - on the queenside. }
