1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Nf3 Bb7 5. a4 Qa5+
{ 5...b4  immediately gives White a better setup with a possible b3 and Bb2. The check prevents that option by forcing the Bishop to d2.  6.Qc2  g6  7.b3  Bg7  8.Bb2  is a sample line. }
6. Bd2 b4 7. Qc2 d6 8. g3
{ 8.e4  This is more classical way to develop. Black has a standard setup almost no matter what White is choosing.  Nbd7  9.Bd3  g6  10.O-O  Bg7  11.Bf4  O-O  12.Nbd2  Qc7  This is Black's setup. He has a harmonious piece placement and intends to play Rae8 and Bc8 soon.  13.h3  e5  14.Be3  Rae8  15.Nh2  Bc8  16.Rfe1  Nh5  Here Black has an easy game in my opinion. White has no clear way forward while Black my play with f5 in the long run.  17.Qd1  Nf4  18.Bc2  Nf6  19.Ndf1  h6  20.Ng3  Nh7  21.Qd2  h5  22.Rab1  h4  23.Ngf1  Bh6  24.Nf3  Qd8  25.N1h2  Ng5  26.b3  Kg7  27.Kh1  Nxf3  28.Nxf3  Rh8  29.Rg1  Nh5  30.Ng5  f6  and Draw agreed in Sokolov,I-Bareev,E/Sarajevo 2000. They could have continued for sure, but it is rather closed. If anybody I'd rather be Black here. }
8... g6 9. Bh3 Bg7 10. O-O O-O 11. e4 Nbd7
{ Black's standard setup can be applied here as well. The White Bishop covers e6, so playing the e-pawn is not that easy for Black here. }
12. Be3
{ 12.Bf4  Qc7  13.Nbd2  Rae8  14.Rae1  Bc8  15.Re2  Nh5  16.Be3  e6  This is a flexible approach. Black is attacking the White d5 pawn and keeps his options open: taking and still playing the pawn to e5 is possible.  17.Rfe1   17.dxe6  fxe6  18.Ng5  Ne5  is fine for Black, heading for c6 and ultimately d4 if possible.  17...Kh8  18.Bg2  e5 !?  Now Black is ready for the f5 push.  19.Ng5  Ndf6  20.h3  Ng8  21.Nf1  f6  22.Nf3  f5  23.exf5  gxf5  24.Bc1  Ne7  25.b3  Ng6  This was played in Liascovich,L-Felgaer,R/Tres de Febrero 2003. Black is fine obviously, having nice ideas with his pawn duo. }
12... Rae8 13. Nbd2 Qc7 14. Rae1 Bc8 15. Nh4
{ 15.Re2  This move was suggested by GM Igor Stohl in his comments for Chessbase Magazine. I think it is a good idea, preparing Ne1-d3 as Stohl mentions. This gives White some ideas with the f-pawn long term.  e6  16.dxe6 !?   16.Rfe1  exd5  17.exd5 =  Is equal according to Stohl.  16...fxe6  17.e5  dxe5  18.Ng5  And White has compensation for the pawn in this interesting position. There were alternatives for Black earlier, but anyhow I think that 15 Nh4 should be replaced with 15 Re2. }
15... Ne5 16. Bxc8
{ 16.Bg2 ?!  Neg4  is very awkward for White and should be avoided. } 16...
Qxc8 17. f3 { White needs to patch some holes on the light squares. } 17... e6
18. b3
{ 18.dxe6  fxe6  doesn't improve either. Black has good chances here, even d6-d5 in on the agenda in some cases. }
18... exd5 19. cxd5
{ Stohl is critical of this move and I guess correctly so. The other recapture still gave White a very solid position, while in the game he is struggling afterwards quite quickly.   19.exd5  Re7  is fine for Black, but White's position is tough to crack. }
19... Qa6 20. Ng2 Re7 21. Kh1
{ 21.f4 ?  This doesn't work at all.  Neg4  22.h3  Nxe3  23.Rxe3  Rfe8  24.Rfe1  Nd7  And White's centre is cracking down.  25.Kh2  Bd4  26.R3e2  Nb6  And the threat of Nxd5 is deadly. }
21... Rc8 22. Rc1 Nd3
{ 22...c4 !  23.Nxc4  Rec7  was even stronger as pointed out by Stohl. } 23.
Rcd1 Nd7
{ 23...Ne5  Black had to take his move basically - we all know how difficult it is. }
24. f4
{ 24.Qc4 !  This is very strong for White, but was missed.  Nb8  25.Qxa6  Nxa6  26.Nc4  Nb2  27.Bg5  Rd7  28.Nxb2  Bxb2  29.Ne3  ±  Black will never get c5-c4, which gives White the great c4 outpost that perfectly supports f4/e5 after due preparation. }
24... Nb2 { Now everything works out perfectly for Black. } 25. Rb1
{ 25.Rc1  c4 !  26.Nxc4  Nxc4  27.bxc4  Bc3 !  is an important detail. Black wins the pawn bakc with an overwhelming position. }
25... c4 26. bxc4 Nxc4 27. Qd3 Nb8 { Forcing matters now. } 28. Nxc4 Qxc4 29.
Qxc4 Rxc4 30. e5
{ Trying for some desparate counterplay, but Black should win with precise play. }
30... Rb7 { 30...dxe5  31.Rfc1  Rxc1+  32.Rxc1  Rb7  should also win. } 31. e6
fxe6 32. dxe6 Re4 33. g4 Rxe6 34. f5 gxf5 35. gxf5 Re4 36. f6 Bf8 37. Bd2 Kf7
38. Ne3 Nd7 { 38...Bh6 ?  39.Nf5  Allowing that is no good idea for Black ! }
39. Nf5 d5 40. Bh6 Re6 41. Bxf8 Kxf8 42. Nd4 Rxf6 43. Rfd1 Ne5 44. Nb5 a6 45.
