1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. bxa6 g6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. e4 O-O 8. Nf3
Qa5 9. Nd2 Bxa6 10. Bxa6 Qxa6 11. Qe2 e6 12. Nc4 Re8
{ This is a tricky move by the creative French GM.   12...exd5  This was a simpler alternative that also would have led to fine play for Black - but it is easier to handle for White.  13.Nxd5 !  This is a better defence.   13.exd5  Re8  14.Ne3   14.Be3  Nh5 !  A very strong move ! Black gets the f7 pawn ready !  15.g3  f5  16.Nd2  The only move to avoid immediate defeat.  f4  17.gxf4  Nxf4  18.Qxa6  Nxa6  19.O-O  Nd3  Black has a very nice initiative. A very common scenario in the Benko is Black regaining the pawn while retaining an active position.  14...Ne4  15.Nxe4  Rxe4  16.Qxa6  This is not helping White at all. The Black Knight gets into the game quickly via b4.  Nxa6  17.O-O  f5  Again with a nice initiative for Black.  13...Nxd5  14.exd5  d6  15.O-O  Nd7  16.Re1  Rfb8  All black pieces are very active, with the g7 Bishop being great in particular. White has no prospects here to convert his pawns as they are under heavy pressure.  17.Bf4  Rb4  18.Rac1  Bxb2 !  19.Rc2   19.Nxb2  Rxf4  is already a lot better for Black.  19...Ne5  20.Bxe5  Bxe5  21.a3  Rb3  22.Nxe5  Qxe2  23.Rcxe2  dxe5  24.Rxe5  Rbxa3  25.d6  Rd8  26.Rxc5  Rxd6  With a drawn endgame. }
13. d6
{ 13.Bg5  This is the only good move available here !  exd5  14.Bxf6  dxc4  15.Bxg7  Kxg7  16.O-O  Nc6  With about equal play in this still interesting position.   13.Be3 ?!  Nxe4 !  14.Nxe4  exd5  15.Ncd6  Re7  16.Qxa6  Nxa6  17.O-O-O  dxe4  And White still needs to be precise to hold. }
13... Nc6 14. O-O
{ 14.Be3  Ng4 !  15.Bxc5  Reb8  16.Rc1  Nge5  17.Nxe5  Nxe5  18.Qxa6  Rxa6  And White is falling apart. }
14... Nd5
{ A very nice shot, but it is not the best move it seems.   14...Reb8  Keeping the tension seems to be stronger.  15.Bf4  Ng4 !  16.Rac1   16.Qxg4  Qxc4  17.Bc1  Ne5  18.Qd1  Nd3  is unbearable for White.  16...Nge5  Again the Queen trade does not worry Black.  17.Nxe5  Qxe2  18.Nxe2  Nxe5  19.Rxc5  Nd3  20.Rc2  Rxb2  21.Rxb2  Bxb2  22.g3  Rxa2  And Black has gotten the pawns back and is better, as e4 and d6 are still weak. }
15. exd5 exd5 16. Ne3 Qxe2 17. Nxe2 d4 18. Nf4 dxe3 19. Bxe3 Bxb2 20. Rab1 Rxa2
{ That long sequence was forced for both sides after 14... Nd5. } 21. Nd5 Re6
22. Bxc5 Bd4 23. Bxd4 Nxd4 { This should lead to a draw now. } 24. Nc7 Ree2 25.
Rb8+ Kg7 26. Ne8+
{ 26.Rd8  Rad2  27.Rxd7  Nf5  28.Nb5  Re5  29.Rb7  Nxd6  That was the easy way to the draw. }
26... Kh6 27. Nf6 Nf5 28. h4
{ 28.Rd8  Rad2  29.Rxd7 ?  Kg7  30.Ng4  h5  Shows White's issues nicely. }
28... Nxh4 29. Nxd7 Rad2 30. Rd8 Nf5 31. Nf6 Nxd6 32. Ng4+ Kg7 33. Nh2 Ne4 34.
Rxd2 Nxd2 35. Rd1 Ne4
{ This is a pain to defend - Black ultimately preveiled. } 36. f3 Nc3 37. Rc1
Nd5 38. Kf1 Rb2 39. Ng4 h5 40. Nf2 Nf4 41. Rd1 Ra2 42. g3 Ne2 43. Kg2 Nc3 44.
